children: Gender Quotas & Representation of Women
in Politics & Public Elections:
A look at the efficacy of gender quotas
Women have chronically been underrepresented in leadership positions, government and politics being no exemption
Descriptive Representation is important because:

Women represented by women are more likely to become interested & involved in politics than women who were represented by men (High-Peppert & Comer, 1998)

Enhanced connection between representatives & constituents, which lead to;

Consequent increase in trust in government & improved attitudes of voters towards their representatives, particularly among underrepresented populations (Mansbridge, 1999; Brunell et al, 2008)

Descriptive representation facilitates substantive representation (Garboni, 2015)
When we talk about 'representation' in the literature, we refer to:
Descriptive Representation
Substantive Representation
women standing for women
representatives acting on behalf of women
Both are important but my datasets and analysis exclusively focus on the former, which is measured by the number of women representatives.
While the number of women in parliament has grown, its growth rate has been an incredibly slow climb.

All but a few countries have yet to reach a gender balance in political institutions. In terms of women reprepresentation, this means political institutions are a far cry from being descriptively representative of the populations they act for.
Quotas act as a mechanism that aims to address this issue
but how effective are they at increasing women's representation in national parliaments?

'women_representation_data': 'Proportions of seats held by women in national parliaments' - World Bank
Data originally sourced from Inter-Parliamentary Union (ipu.org)
'gender_quota_data': 'Gender Quota Database' - International Institute for Democracy and Electoral Assitance (IDEA)
About my datasets:

Original women representation dataset had individual years in columns rather than 'year' as a column and each year as a value

No key to merge datasets

Regional grouping

Kmeans doesn't work on categorical variables and I couldn't figure out how to implement Kmodes
Top issues with my datasets:
Most countries' governments comprise of only one level of legislature (unicameral) but bicameral parliaments have, on average, higher proportion of women in their legislature.
Legislated candidate quotas are more popular than reserved seats
One possible reason could be that bicameral governments are more likey to have some form of quotas than unicameral ones
However, it's not for certain - at most levels they seem like they work but we can't be enitrely sure just yet.
Finding 1:
Bicameral Parliaments consistently elect more women into parliament than unicameral parliaments & countries that have no known quotas
And countries that have voluntary political party quotas consistently elect more women into parliament than countries that do not
Countries with quotas at lower/single house level appointing more women in public office than countries without, particularly after 2005
We see the same pattern, of similar variants, occuring at the upper house
And at the sub-national level as well
Findings from this series of graphs reaffirm that quotas are better than no quotas at all when it comes to electing more women in parliament.

Further, it's worth noting that in the parliament type chart, we also see a category called unknown, and these are the countries who did not appear in the gender quota dataset and are otherwise not known to have gender quota systems at all.

These unknown countries elected less women over time compared to unicameral parliament types, who by virtue of the fact that they exist in the dataset means that they have some quota system in place, demonstrating that irrespective of parliament types, quotas do seem to work, at least on average over time.
We see the same pattern for all the other plotted variables - that some form of quota is better on average than no quota at all.
What this series doesn't tell us, however, is what kind of setup or even which quota system works best. To answer that question, we're going to have to create a different plot.
Finding 2:
Top performing countries have quotas in at least one level of public office but so do least performing countries

From the aforementioned sections, I was expecing to find that the top performing countries would have more quotas set up and that the bottom performing countries would not have any quotas set up at all.
This turned out to be half true

The top performing countries were indeed mostly bicameral parliament types and did indeed have quotas in place. As expected, most of them did have quotas in place for more than one level of government.
But countries with the least average number of women in parliament over time ALSO had quotas in place in at least one level.
Means that while having quotas are better than non-quotas in general, this chart actually shows that quotas dont necessarily guarantee the election of more women in parliaments
This finding is in line with the literature on the efficacy of quotas (Gwiazda, 2017; Schwidnt-Bayer, 2011)
Finding 3:
Do gender quotas result in more women elected into legislatures?
Ans: Yes they do but they're not a guarantee. More detailed analysis needs to be done on under what circumstances are quotas effective/ineffecitve .

#extract country names and create a new list, repeating country names 24 times
country_names = countries_data['country_name']
country_names = np.repeat(country_names, 24)

#create a new dataframe, inserting country_names list into the first column 
women_representation_df = pd.DataFrame(country_names).reset_index().drop(['index'], axis = 1)

#do the same for country codes
country_code = countries_data['country_code']
country_code = list(np.repeat(country_code,24))
women_representation_df['country_code'] = country_code

#repeat for year
years = list(range(1997,2021))
n = countries_data['country_name'].nunique()
years = years*n
women_representation_df['year'] = years

#Finally, flip the values that's meant to be percent_of_women so that the value corresponds with the correct country and year
#To do this, I know that I just have to create a list and stack all the float rows on top of each other 

#first, extract the relevant columns
stacked_data= pd.DataFrame(countries_data.iloc[:,2:])
#flip it and stack it but don't drop the na, otherwise it won't match the index
stacked_data = list(stacked_data.stack(dropna = False))
#place the newly stacked list into the dataframe
women_representation_df['percent_of_women'] = stacked_data
women_representation_df.head(10)

children: First I will extract the country names from the countries_data dataset into a new list called country_names and repeat it for the number of times as there are years. In this case, there are 23 years between 1997 and 2020 so I will repeat it 24 times;
Next, I will create a new dataframe and add my country_names list to it
I will repeat the same steps for country code and year, calling the columns country_code and year respectively;
Finally, I will flip the percent_of_women to complete my dataset.

children: Convert the country_code in both datasets to the ISO2 code. Doing this ensures some form of consistency across both datasets for when I assign region names later on. If the country cannot be identified, I will first class it with 'Unknown code' and manually replace them after.
Next, I will create 7 lists, reprsenting each regional category as mentioned above.

Each list will contain the ISO2 code of the countries classed in those regions, according to the following source:https://datahelpdesk.worldbank.org/knowledgebase/articles/906519-world-bank-country-and-lending-groups
After creating these 7 lists, I will extract the respective countries for each regional list and concatenate them into a new dataframe, adding the regions column.

Naturally, I expect there to be some countries who were left out from this process so I will cross check my new dataframe and my countries_data to identify which countries they are and manually assign them based on a simple google search.

* other than the first, the last two are quota systems that can be written via legislation or constitution and can also be either enforced via penalities for non-compliance or not..
Types of Quotas:
Voluntary Political Party Quotas: rules/targets set by political parties to include a certain % of women as candidates
Legislated Candidate Quotas: requires that a minimum number of candidates are women
Reserved Seats: requires that a minimum number of seats in the legislature are held by women
Types of Parliaments:
Unicameral : One level of legislature (E.g. Folketing of Denmark; National Assembly of Cuba)
Bicameral : Two chambers of legislation (E.g. House of Commons & House of Lords in the UK; Congree & Senate in the US)
